<DOC><DOCNO> AP880802-0031 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0218EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-02 0694</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,600</SECOND><HEAD>Hospital Ordered to Justify Hinckley Field Trip</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: St. Elizabeths without apostrophe is cq</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge has given St. Elizabethsmental hospital until Friday to submit treatment records supportingits conclusion that residential assailant John W. Hinckley Jr.should be allowed a day trip off hospital grounds.   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker on Monday granted arequest by prosecutors for a court hearing on the hospital proposalto let Hinckley go on a supervised ``recreational'' field trip withother patients.   Hinckley, who shot and wounded President Reagan and three otherson March 31, 1981, has been held at St. Elizabeths since 1982, whenhe was acquitted of criminal charges by reason of insanity.   Last year, the government successfully opposed an attempt byhospital authorities to allow Hinckley to visit his parents overthe Easter weekend.   The Secret Service said it opposed the hospital's latest plan,which was outlined in a July 19 letter to the judge.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Pryor Bill Would Require Registration of Consultants</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sen. David Pryor, responding to allegations ofcorruption in the nation's defense contracting, has proposedrequiring private consultants to defense contractors to registerwith the federal government.   ``The bill is intended to shed some sunshine on theall-too-shadowy world of consultants. Bringing everything into thelight should cut down on the shady dealings,'' Pryor, D-Ark., saidafter introducing the bill Monday.   Pryor chairs the Senate Government Affairs federal servicesubcommittee, which has held a series of hearings on the use ofconsultants by Pentagon contractors.   Prosecutors are investigating allegations that contractors'consultants, many of them former Pentagon employees, paid bribes tocurrent Defense Department workers for inside information aboutcontracts. No charges have been filed.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Saudis Say They Still Want US Weaponry</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Saudi Arabia is seeking to bolster its weaponsstockpile from nations around the world even though it still wantsto buy arms from the United States, its major supplier for years.   The Saudi embassy, seeking to dispel notions of a U.S.-Saudirift, released a statement Monday on their decision to buy $17billion worth of military equipment from Britain.   ``The kingdom would like to reiterate its desire to obtain itsmilitary requirements, including advanced aircraft and defensearms, from American plants, with the full conviction of ourpeaceful intentions..,'' the statement said. It was attributed toan unnamed source who was quoted by the Saudi Press Agency.   The State Department has complained that the deal with Britain,which includes 50 Tornado jet fighters, was not in the interest ofthe United States.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Reagan Hears Arguments on Anti-Pollution Pact</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan is expected to decide soon onwhether the U.S. will participate in a treaty aimed at stemming apollutant that can lead to acid rain.   Reagan and his Cabinet's Domestic Policy Council heard argumentsMonday for and against U.S. participation in a plan to freezeemissions of oxides in nitrogen, which is produced by industry,utilities and motor vehicles.   The council was briefed on a proposal coming from a UnitedNations-sponsored negotiation that would freeze emissions until1996, pending further research on the effects of nitrogen oxidesand how to reduce them.   According to two participants in discussions over the issue,both of whom spoke on condition of anonymity, the EnvironmentalProtection Agency supports joining the treaty while the EnergyDepartment, supported by the Interior and Commerce departments andthe Office of Management and Budget, opposes it.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Government Ordered To Change Secrecy Pledge</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government must change or delete languagein pledges signed by 1.7 million government workers not to disclosetop-secret information that a federal judge says isunconstitutionally vague.   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch ordered the modification in thenon-disclosure pledges signed by government workers with access tosecret information must sign to retain their security clearances.   In the order signed Friday and made public Monday, the judgesaid the government must provide a more specific definition of theterm ``classifiable information.''   In signing the various pledges, government employees promise notto make unauthorized disclosures of top-secret information or``classifiable information.''</TEXT></DOC>